Introduction

The following analyses is based on â€œGene Expression of Endangered Coral (Orbicella spp.) in Flower Garden Banks National Marine Sanctuary After Hurricane Harveyâ€ (Wright et. al.Â 2019). After Hurricane Harvey, tissue samples were collected to study the impacts of the freshwater runoff on coral and symbionts. These samples were collected at two time points: September 2017 (stress) and October 2017 (recover) to study the gene expression of Orbicella faveolata and Orbicella franksi. Also studied was Breviolum minutum, an algal symbiont which showed differentially expressed genes (DEGs) at different sampling time points. This may be the algal symbiontâ€™s response to the freshwater event (change in habitat). The purpose of our assignment was to study these DEGs at two time points, the stress and recovery. By utilizing arrayQualityMetrics, we were able to identify one outlier. DESeq2 was leveraged to identify these DEGs and create a statistical model to study the expression patterns. Our findings indicate that gene expression of algal symbionts groups by recovery vs.Â stress conditions. The majority of differentially expressed genes are upregulated during recovery relative to stress conditions, indicating that recovery following stressful periods leads to upregulation of symbiont gene pathways. Overall, our findings suggest that algal symbionts of coral hosts enact different gene expression pathways when exposed to and recovering from stressful events.

The sample fav_stressC was detected as an outlier via the Distances between arrays method (Figure X) and MA plot method (Figure X). For the purpose of this assignment, we will include it due to our very low sample size, but in a real scenario, we would exclude it.

We next converted the counts data, treatment information, and desired statistical model into a DESeq object so that we can work with the data in DESeq.

dds=DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData=countData,
                           colData = g,
                           design = ~treat)
vsd.ge=assay(vst(dds))
rl=vst(dds)
e=ExpressionSet(assay(rl), AnnotatedDataFrame(as.data.frame(colData(rl))))
arrayQualityMetrics(e, intgroup=c("treat"),force=T)

One step DESeq does the following: estimates size factors, estimates dispersions, generates gene-wise dispersion estimates, generates the mean-dispersion relationship, final dispersion estimates, and fits and tests the model.

dds<-DESeq(dds)

These results allow us to make sure nothing abnormal is going on. The post-normalized counts are pvalues that correspond to how differentially expressed a gene is between treatments. padj adjusts pvalues for multiple tests. The baseMean is the average count for one comparison (whichever treatment group came first). log2FoldChange shows differentiation in counts between the basemean vs other treatment group. The recovery treatment group had avg of 5.57 counts; stress group had a 2fold change (logtransformed).

Stress vs.Â recovery comparison to identify differentially expressed genes

We can only do pairwise comparisons. Levels are used because gene expression is always relative; the first term is the treatment and the second term is the one thatâ€™s relative (treatment 1st, control 2nd).

colData$Stress<-factor(colData$treat, levels=c("Stress","Recovery"))
resStress <- results(dds, contrast=c("treat","Stress","Recovery"))

False discovery rate pvalues are adjusted to < 10%

Adjusting P-Values & Log Transforming Data

P-values were initially found by running DESeq2 and contrasting functions. These indicate whether the number of differentially expressed genes between Stressed and Recovery samples were significantly different or not. Each p-value correlates to a gene. If a geneâ€™s p-value is significant (set at a threshold of <0.01), it suggests that itâ€™s differentially expressed between the two samples.

We used the following code to create a table comparing the original p-values to the adjusted p-values. P-values are adjusted to reduce error.

valStress=cbind(resStress$pvalue, resStress$padj)
colnames(valStress)=c("pval.Stress", "padj.Stress")

The total amount of p-values calculated, including samples with no or low counts, is 31999. This can be found using the following code:

length(valStress[,1])

5093 of the 31999 reads had low-count data resulting in NAâ€™s; these were found and removed using the following code:

table(complete.cases(valStress))

Principal Components Analysis

rld_t=t(rld)

pc2v <- round(li[2] * 100, 1)
pca_s <- as.data.frame(pca$x)

Figure 6. Principal components analysis of gene expression of stress vs recovery samples. The gene expression of the samples groups by stress vs recovery.

From this plot, we can see that the symbiont gene expression of the samples groups by treatment (stress vs.Â recovery). Together, the first two principal components explain 49.5% of the variance in the data. The percentage of variance explained is likely low because we only included 6 samples in the analysis.

To see if the clustering of gene expression of the two treatments on the principal component axes is significantly different, we run an analysis of variance with distance matrices.

adonis(pca$x ~ treat, data = pca_s, method='eu', na.rm = TRUE)

However, because of our low sample size and strong visual clustering of treatments on the plotted PCA, we conclude that there is likely a difference in the gene expression of coral symbionts in the stressed versus recovery conditions.

Conclusion

Our findings indicate that gene expression of algal symbionts groups by recovery vs.Â stress conditions. The majority of differentially expressed genes are upregulated during recovery relative to stress conditions, indicating that recovery following stressful periods leads to upregulation of symbiont gene pathways. Overall, our findings suggest that algal symbionts of coral hosts enact different gene expression pathways when exposed to and recovering from stressful events.
